\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Interpretability diagnostics for the revised extensions. Left: the reference-split MLP meta-controller keeps the largest weight on \texttt  {D\_cvar\_robust} while adaptively reallocating the remainder across regime rules and LinUCB, which explains why it improves on the standalone learners while still remaining below \texttt  {D+}. Right: convexity mode usage for \texttt  {D\_plus\_convexity} shifts from mostly \texttt  {none} in bull states to mostly \texttt  {strong} in bear states. The figure supports the paper's headline mechanism claim: the gains come from state-dependent distribution shaping and expert selection, not from a new predictive signal.}}{18}{figure.caption.19}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:interpretability}{{6}{18}{Interpretability diagnostics for the revised extensions. Left: the reference-split MLP meta-controller keeps the largest weight on \texttt {D\_cvar\_robust} while adaptively reallocating the remainder across regime rules and LinUCB, which explains why it improves on the standalone learners while still remaining below \texttt {D+}. Right: convexity mode usage for \texttt {D\_plus\_convexity} shifts from mostly \texttt {none} in bull states to mostly \texttt {strong} in bear states. The figure supports the paper's headline mechanism claim: the gains come from state-dependent distribution shaping and expert selection, not from a new predictive signal}{figure.caption.19}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Left-tail empirical distribution diagnostic for the reference split. Compared with factor-only and plain CVaR, \texttt  {D+} shifts the worst-return mass inward and improves the 5\% tail summary while leaving average return roughly unchanged relative to plain \texttt  {D}. The improvement of \texttt  {D+} is therefore driven primarily by tail-risk reduction rather than by higher average returns alone.}}{18}{figure.caption.20}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:taildiagnostic}{{7}{18}{Left-tail empirical distribution diagnostic for the reference split. Compared with factor-only and plain CVaR, \texttt {D+} shifts the worst-return mass inward and improves the 5\% tail summary while leaving average return roughly unchanged relative to plain \texttt {D}. The improvement of \texttt {D+} is therefore driven primarily by tail-risk reduction rather than by higher average returns alone}{figure.caption.20}{}}
